of salvation; but in line 22 the focus shifts from Mary as object of
praise to Dante ^personaggio~ as supplicant, and the remainder of the
prayer has a function more practical than celebratory. Lines 1-21 thus
provide Bernard with an opportunity to display his credentials as a
Mariologist, which he does in a passage as notable for its theological
authority as for its verbal bravura; lines 22-39, on the other hand,
show that characteristically Bernardine combination of doctrine and
eloquence placed at the service of an urgent and specific purpose within
the narrative. Bernard has something to ask for; and it is the efficacy
of his speech that ensures that he gets it" (^Dante and the Mystical
Tradition~, Cambridge UP, 1994, p. 110).

